Not So Sunny Southern California:
Classifying Drought Conditions in Los Angeles County, California

Nick Vastine
DTSA 5742 - Predicting Extreme Climate Behavior with Machine Learning
Final Project
March 3, 2025

Abstract¶

Wildfires in Southern California at the start of 2025 accounted for the 2nd and 3rd most destructive wildfires in California's history ("Top 20 Most Destructive California Wildfires" Cal FIRE). In the densely populated Los Angeles County with increasing frequent drought conditions, it is valuable to understand the underlying indicators to accurately classify drought conditions.

This report considers temperature, soil moisture, and groundwater data from USGS, NOAA, and US Drought Monitor to build binary drought classification models. Data was imported, cleaned, aggregated, and standardized prior to model training. A binary drought classification metric was developed, though future work could perform regression on the Drought Severity and Coverage Index (DSCI).

Principal Component Analysis (PCA) was performed not to reduce dimensionality, but instead to identify soil temperature and moisture as similar predictors in the first principal component.

Several machine learning algorithms for drought classification were compared including decision trees, random forests, logistic classification, Support Vector Classification (SVC) and neural networks. A sensitifty study on the architecture of neural networks by varying layers and neurons was performed, indicating the value of a second layer and limited correlation between model accuracy and the number of neurons. Classification models also compared the effects of standardizing the data prior to model training, which had the most effect on support vector classification.

While many models performed at 90%+ accuracy, the random forest ensemble method performed best with 98.4% accuracy. Models were also investigated for the most important predictors to drought classification, which was primarily groundwater level followed by soil temperature.

These models are limited in application to Los Angeles Country and rely on assuming that future drought will reflect historic conditions. Further analysis could consider regression analysis on DSCI, consider predictive modeling from current conditions, and experiment further with model tuning such as by varying hyperparameters or exploring neural network implementations.

0. Introduction¶

Wildfires across Southern California in early 2025 were ranked among the worst in California history (“Statistics.” Cal FIRE). In 2025 alone, more than 57,000 acres have burned, claimed 29 lives, and 16,000 structures have been destroyed ("The Department of Forestry and Fire Protection" Cal FIRE). Of the top 20 most destructive wildfires in California history, 15 have occured in the past 10 years ("Top 20 Most Destructive California Wildfires" Cal FIRE).

There are many contributors to the devastation created by wildfires in recent years, such as hurricane force winds, low humidity in the winter, and accumulation of vegetation (Keeley). Southern California is also affected by the El Nino Southern Oscillation (ENSO) which further affects shifts in precipitation ("El Nino." California Coastal Commission) Southern California has faced drought conditions for 50.6% of the past 10 years by this report's calculation ("Comprehensive Statistics." U.S. Drought Monitor)

With the dramatic loss of life and property from these wildfire events, it is valuable to classify drought conditions in Southern California via a model. Los Angeles county has a population of 9.663 million people, which is greater than 40 states in the United States ("QuickFacts Los Angeles County, California." United States Census Bureau). Thus, investigating an area where drought can affect millions of individuals is valuable for policy decisions or resource management.

This analysis seeks to understand the indicators of drought drawing from numerous government data sources to accurate classify drought conditions via supervised learning.

1. Methodology¶

The drought analysis of Los Angeles County occurs in several steps, from API data collection through comparative analysis of supervised learning methods.

First, data is collected, cleaned, and aggregated from several government data sources. Exploratory data analysis is performed at each data import to identify any trends and adjust for any suspicious data.

Once data is collected, a Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is performed to analyze feature similarity. Since there are relatively few features to describe our drought conditions, PCA is performed solely as an exploratory study and does not create features for supervised learning.

Data is then split into a testing and training set. This study also assesses the effect of standardized features on model performance, so a scaled training/testing set is also created.

Five supervised learning methods are compared to identify the classification model with the highest accuracy. These methods include: decision tree, random forest, logistic classification, support vector machines, and neural networks. Methods are implemented with default settings where available. A sensitivity study is performed on neural network architecture, evaluating different neuron counts in 1 or 2 layer networks.

1.1.1 Groundwater Level¶

Groundwater level is sourced from a US Geological Survey site. While technically there are no USGS stations measuring groundwater within Los Angeles county, there are groundwater measurements in the neighboring city of San Bernardino.

USGS Site 340804117221604 is imported below using the NWIS Data Retrieval API. The data is then cleaned to isolate the date and median groundwater features, and null values are removed.

A summary plot is presented below the imported information. Note that groundlevel may appear misleading since a receding water level appears as an increase in the groundwater plot. As such, the plot shows a gradually receding groundwater level in San Bernardino without major seasonal variation. A histogram accompanies the plots, which indicates a stagnating water level in recent years.

1.1.2 Streamflow¶

It is challenging to identify a suitable streamflow site since many of Los Angeles' waterways are dammed to limit flow, thus measuring the flow above or below the dam could lead to different conclusions. For example, flow measurements upstream of the dam may represent preciptitation more directly, while measurements downstream of the dam may instead reflect drought expectations (i.e. downstream flow is fully restricted if drought is expected). There is additional streamflow nuance considering water rights and how much water must be passed through a dam, even under local drought conditions.

After reviewing some site options, the report collects streamflow information from USGS Site 11092450. This site is directly on the Los Angeles River and has consistently available data since 2002. The site also collected a variety of information such as dissolved oxygen, pH, phycocyanin fluorescence... indicating the site's importance.

The below code imports the data, isolates relevant information, removes null values, then plots the streamflow information. Interestingly, the plot appears to show some seasonality, with a significant spike in discharge at least once per year. The accompanying histogram also indicates the generally low average discharge, which has been labeled with a red dashed line.

1.1.3 Soil Moisture and Soil Temperature¶

Soil Moisture and Temperature information is collected from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) using HTTP requests. Note there is limited data available in Los Angeles County, so soil data is captured from the neighboring city of Santa Barbara.

The below code imports the dataset, then isolates the Soil Moisture Volumetric Water Content (SMVWC) and Soil Temperature at depths of 10, 20, and 50 cm. SMVWC represents the volume of water per unit volume of soil, ranging from 0.0 (0% water) to 1.0 (100% water). These features are labeled sm_Xcm and st_Xcm respectively, where X denotes the soil depth of the measurement.

The data is then plotted, first separately showing the moisture and temperature at a range of depths over time. The data is then plotted together, grouping moisture and temperature data.

In [6]:
# Data sourced from NOAA - https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/data/us-climate-reference-network/access/derived-products/soil/soilanom/
csv_url = 'https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/data/us-climate-reference-network/access/derived-products/soil/soilanom/CRNSSM0101-CA_Santa_Barbara_11_W.csv'
df_soil = pd.read_csv(csv_url)

# Isolate Soil Moisture Volumetric Water Content (SMVWC) and Soil Temperature (ST)
# at 10, 20, and 50 cm depths
df_soil = df_soil[['DATE_TIME',
                   'SMVWC_10_CM', 'ST_10_CM',
                   'SMVWC_20_CM', 'ST_20_CM',
                   'SMVWC_50_CM', 'ST_50_CM']]
df_soil['DATE_TIME'] = pd.to_datetime(df_soil['DATE_TIME'],  # Clean up dates
                                      format='%Y%m%d%H')     
df_soil['DATE_TIME'] = df_soil['DATE_TIME'].dt.date            
df_soil = df_soil.groupby('DATE_TIME').mean().reset_index()  # Average multiple entries
df_soil.dropna(inplace=True)                                 # Drop null
df_soil.rename(columns={'DATE_TIME': 'date',                 # Rename for ease
                            'SMVWC_10_CM': 'sm_10cm', 'ST_10_CM': 'st_10cm',
                            'SMVWC_20_CM': 'sm_20cm', 'ST_20_CM': 'st_20cm',
                            'SMVWC_50_CM': 'sm_50cm', 'ST_50_CM': 'st_50cm'}, inplace=True)
# Soil Temperature at X depth (st_Xcm), Soil Moisture at X depth (sm_Xcm)
df_soil.reset_index()
df_soil.head(1)

As mentioned, Southern California would be affected by the ENSO cycle, though this is not apparent from soil moisture data alone. 1.1.4 Temperature and Precipitation¶

Temperature and precipitation data is collected from NOAA, though this time from their NCEI Data Service API.

The Los Angeles International Airport, NOAA Station USW00023174, was selected as it includes mostly complete data for temperature and precipitation. The following code imports the data since 2010 through the end of 2024.

In [10]:
## NOAA NCEI Import
# ** Due to API record limits, data is imported incrementally and consolidated **

# Generate date list for incremental export
date_list = []
for year in range(2010,2025):
    for month_start,month_end in [("-01-01","-06-30"),("-07-01","-12-31")]:
        date_list.append((str(year)+month_start,str(year)+month_end)) 
# Station
station = ['GHCND:USW00023174']
# HTTP Requests
url = 'https://www.ncei.noaa.gov/cdo-web/api/v2/data'
headers = {'token':'HQvmpIfClwoToZoPmOrIxNNvqqstpWXm'} # Passed in requests
# Initialize dataframe
df_NOAA = pd.DataFrame()
# Import incrementally, by date
for start,end in date_list: 
#    print("Current Date Import: ",start,end)
    # HTTP Request
    payload = {'datasetid':'GHCND','stationid':station,'startdate':start, 'enddate':end, 'datatypeid':['TMAX','TMIN','PRCP'], 'limit':1000, 'units':'standard'}
    r = requests.get(url, params=payload, headers=headers)
    while r.status_code == 503: # Check for server unavailable
        print("Request Error: ", r.status_code) 
        r = requests.get(url, params=payload, headers=headers) # re-run request if server was unavailable until it works
    r.raise_for_status()  # raises exception when not a 2xx response
    # Processing Request
    data = r.json()
    live_df = pd.json_normalize(data['results']) # Data is imported such that each station/date/item is its own line
    grouped_df = live_df.groupby(['station','date', 'datatype'])['value'].first().unstack().reset_index() 
        # groupby() put values in station/date/datatype order.
        # first() takes the first value of each group (if there were redundancies)
        # unstack() pivots from long to wide format based on the datatype
    # Saving data
    df_NOAA = pd.concat([df_NOAA, grouped_df], ignore_index = True) # Add to running total
    #df_NOAA.to_csv("NOAA Data Export.csv")
print("Import Complete!")
#df_NOAA.to_csv("NOAA Data Export - Complete.csv")

1.1.5 Drought Data¶

The final step before we can begin our model training is to establish our target data. The drought data is represented as a percentage of area falling into the following categories [1]

  • D4 - Exceptional Drought (0-2 percentile)
  • D3 - Extreme Drought (2-5 percentile)
  • D2 - Severe Drought (5-10 percentile)
  • D1 - Moderate Drought (10-20 percentile)
  • D0 - Abnormally Dry (20-30 percentile)
  • None or 0 - Neither Wet or Dry

Drought data is downloaded from the Drought Monitor tool web service using the following parameters:

  • Area = CountyStatistics
  • Statistics Type = GetDroughtSeverityStatisticsByAreaPercent
  • Area of Interest (AOI) = 06037, Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) code for Los Angeles County
  • Start Date = 1/1/2010
  • End Date = 1/1/2025
  • Statistics Format = 2, categorical labeling rather than cumulative

A visualization of the region can be found on the Drought Monitor website.

In [14]:
## Drought data import
# Data source: https://droughtmonitor.unl.edu/DmData/DataDownload/ComprehensiveStatistics.aspx
# Documentation: https://droughtmonitor.unl.edu/DmData/DataDownload/WebServiceInfo.aspx#comp
# URL to modify: https://usdmdataservices.unl.edu/api/[area]/[statistics type]?aoi=[aoi]&startdate=[start date]&enddate=[end date]&statisticsType=[statistics format]
drought_url = "https://usdmdataservices.unl.edu/api/CountyStatistics/GetDroughtSeverityStatisticsByAreaPercent?aoi=06037&startdate=1/1/2010&enddate=1/1/2025&statisticsType=2"
df_drought = pd.read_csv(drought_url)
df_drought.head(1)
Out[14]:
MapDate FIPS County State None D0 D1 D2 D3 D4 ValidStart ValidEnd StatisticFormatID
0 20241231 6037 Los Angeles County CA 0.0 16.12 83.88 0.0 0.0 0.0 2024-12-31 2025-01-06 2

The data is provided with a ValidStart and ValidEnd date. In essence, this data is generated by recording drought conditions once each week. These conditions are assumed constant for the entire week.

Rather than isolate these single measurements using ValidStart, we will duplicate the weekly data point for each day within the ValidStart to ValidEnd period. This allows us to transform weekly data into daily data points, cohesive with our daily-reported predictors.

A stacked bar chart of the drought conditions is presented below the cleaned data.

In [15]:
## Drought Data Clean-up
# Remove unnecessary columns
df_drought = df_drought.drop(['MapDate','FIPS','County','State','StatisticFormatID'], axis=1)
# Convert to date time
df_drought['ValidStart'] = pd.to_datetime(df_drought['ValidStart'])
df_drought['ValidEnd'] = pd.to_datetime(df_drought['ValidEnd'])
# Create new date column which is a list of days from ValidStart to ValidEnd
# ex. 1/1/2010 to 1/7/2010 becomes [1/1/2010, 1/2/2010, 1/3/2010, ...]
df_drought['date'] = df_drought.apply(lambda x: pd.date_range(start=x['ValidStart'], end=x['ValidEnd'], freq='D'), axis=1)
# "Explode", duplicating the row for each element in the date list. 
df_drought = df_drought.explode('date')
df_drought.drop(['ValidStart','ValidEnd'], axis=1, inplace=True)
# Sorting the dataframe by date
df_drought = df_drought.sort_values(by='date')
# Dropping rows with duplicate dates
df_drought = df_drought.drop_duplicates(subset='date', keep='first')
# Resetting the index
df_drought = df_drought.reset_index(drop=True)
# Updating date object
df_drought['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df_drought['date'])
df_drought['date'] = df_drought['date'].dt.date
df_drought.to_parquet('target.parquet')

We will create a binary target field to classify if drought is occurring. There does not appear to be a single criteria to classify a larger area as in drought. The US Drought Monitor Drought Classification Resource provides example percentiles for each predictor, but does not clearly state 'if X exceeds __ %, the entire area is under drought'. Thus, I will be applying my best judgement in labeling this dataset.

The aformentioned classification resource suggests >30% of area under normal conditions is typical. Thus, we will mark any day with <30% normal or abnormally dry (D0) conditions as under drought.

In [17]:
## Drought Labeling
df_drought['target'] = 0
df_drought.loc[(df_drought['None']+df_drought['D0']) < 30,'target'] = 1

1.2 Unsupervised Machine Learning - Principal Component Analysis¶

Our final data set has 11 features, which is reasonable for our supervised learning analysis. However, we can perform Principal Component Analysis (PCA), an unsupervised machine learning technique, to understand the influence of our individual features.

First the dataset drops date, our binary drought feature, and our calculated DSCI. We then scale the data to avoid feature magnitude from biasing the PCA analysis.

In [24]:

pca_model = PCA(n_components = 0.9, svd_solver = 'full').fit(df_pca_scaled)

The PCA solver determined 5 principal components are necessary to explain 90% of the variance in our data, as reflected in the below scree plot.

The classifier evaluation function below takes the classifier of interest and returns the accuracy metrics in a dataframe, as well as our models for further consideration.

In [32]:
## Classifier Eval Function
def classifier_eval(classifier,label):
    ## Model creation and fit
    # Non-standard
    model = classifier
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_model = model.predict(X_test)
    # Standard
    model_standard = classifier
    model_standard.fit(X_scaled_train, y_train)
    y_model_standard = model_standard.predict(X_scaled_test)

    ## Accuracy
    # Non-Standard
    acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_model)
    rec = recall_score(y_test, y_model)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_model)
    # Standard
    acc_standard = accuracy_score(y_test, y_model_standard)
    rec_standard = recall_score(y_test, y_model_standard)
    f1_standard = f1_score(y_test, y_model_standard)
    
    data_eval = {'Model':label,
               'Feature':['Original', 'Standardized'],
               'Accuracy':[acc, acc_standard],
               'Recall':[rec, rec_standard],
               'F1 Score':[f1, f1_standard]}
    
    df_eval = pd.DataFrame(data_eval)
    df_eval.set_index(['Model','Feature'],inplace=True)
    return df_eval, model, model_standard

1.4.5 Neural Network¶

Finally we will compare our other supervised machine learning methods to a neural network. Of course there are no 'default settings' for a neural network. As such, this section explores the effect of neural network architecture on its performance.

The following code performs a sensitivity analysis on a 2-hidden layer neural network. The first layer will include 5, 10, or 15 neurons. The second layer will include 1, 5, 10, or 15 neurons. This results in 12 combinations, including effectively collapsing the second layer to a single neuron to represent a single hidden layer network.

The neural networks will be trained for a maximum 150 epochs, sharing the default learning rate with learning rate reduction across models. Batch size will be fixed at about 5% of the training data at 100 samples.

In [41]:
## Build Neural Network Function
def build_neural_network(n1,n2,mode='all'):
    model = keras.Sequential([
        layers.Dense(n1, activation="leaky_relu", name="layer1", kernel_initializer=tf.keras.initializers.LecunNormal()),
        layers.Dense(n2, activation="leaky_relu", name="layer2", kernel_initializer=tf.keras.initializers.LecunNormal()),
        layers.Dense(1,  activation="sigmoid",    name="Output")
    ])
    optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(clipnorm=True)
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy','recall','F1Score'])
    # Early Stopping
    es = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3, verbose=0, restore_best_weights=True)
    # Learning Rate Reduction
    rlrnop = tf.keras.callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', patience=1, verbose=0)
    # Training
    start = time()
    log = model.fit(X_scaled_train, y_train, validation_data=(X_scaled_test, y_test), epochs=150, batch_size=100, callbacks=[es, rlrnop], verbose=0)
    duration = time()-start
    # Logging model performance
    model_loss = log.history['loss'][-1]
    model_val_loss = log.history['val_loss'][-1]
    model_acc = log.history['accuracy'][-1]
    model_val_acc = log.history['val_accuracy'][-1]
    model_val_recall = log.history['recall'][-1]
    model_val_f1 = log.history['F1Score'][-1]
    epoch = len(log.history['loss'])
    if mode == 'all':
        return model_loss, model_val_loss, model_acc, model_val_acc, epoch, duration
    else:
        return model_val_acc, model_val_recall, model_val_f1

2. Results¶

While analysis of results has been performed throughout the modeling process, the following sections evaluate the importance of each predictor based on model feedback, and evaluate which model performed best based on accuracy.

2.1 Predictor Importance¶

While we are ultimately curious to determine which model performs best, the candidate models can provide insight into which predictors are more important for drought prediction.

The table indicates groundwater level, soil temperature, and soil moisture are the most important features across the models. One way to calculate the cross-model importance is to sum the the relative magnitude of the feature within each method. Some additional code Max/Min scales the features from 0 to 1 before summing across the models. The logistic classification uses the absolute value of the coefficient since only its magnitude indicates importance. On the far right we see the resulting Absolute Min Max Scaled sum. A value of 3 indicates that the feature gwl, representing groundwater, was the most important feature across all three models. Soil temperature and soil moisture are also important.

Recall the PCA indicated similarity across the soil temperature and moisture features, and thus their importance may be spread across these variables instead of consolidated into a single PCA component.

Also note that neural networks are much harder to interpret feature importance, and as such are not included in this analysis. This is also a short coming of non-linear kernel SVM methods, a clear shortcoming of both methodologies.

2.2 Accuracy Comparison¶

Knowing which feature is most important is valuable, but identifying features alone does not provide predictions.

The below code aggregates the validation accuracy, recall, and F1 score for the various models. Note the best performing neural network is included from our selection, but the network is re-generated since the individual models were not saved.

The results are ordered based on model test data accuracy.

Notably the decision tree methods perform best on the classification problem. As noted, SVC perform better on standardized variables, while decision trees methods appear minimally affected by standardization. Logistic regression performed worst as a method, potentially due to the non-linearity of our predictor variables. The neural network performed poorly relative to decision trees, with the additional shortcoming that is it a harder model to interpret.

The results of this analysis is that the random forest decision tree ensemble methodology is best for this drought classification problem. Below is a comparison of the actual drought data and the predicted drought data from the random forest model, indicating strong agreement.

3. Limitations¶

While the various models have proven accurate, there are always limitations to any machine learning model.

Since a supervised learning model must be trained, the resulting model is only valid if the future data reflects the training data. For example, this particular model is only valid for predicting drought in the Los Angeles area since it was trained on Los Angeles drought data. The model is invalid for predicting drought in the Amazon rainforest, for example.

The model is also limited to the chosen features including soil moisture, temperature, and groundwater level. If a new predictor were found (such as snowfall metrics or social indicators like water usage), the existing model would need to be re-trained for that predictor.

While this model relies on data collected since 2010, models based on older datasets may have intrinsic assumptions not detailed as their own predictors. For example, a model may consider groundwater depletion as an indicator of drought, but the model may not isolate the effects of growing population demand vs. reduction in precipitation as a cause. In essence, using a single variable without understanding the underlying causation inherently introduces assumptions (and therefore limitations) to the model.

Models may also not be deterministic and can find different solutions based on sampling, batch size, etc. In particular, there was wide variation in the neural network sensitivity analysis to draw neat conclusions about which architecture consistently performs most accurately.

4. Conclusion¶

Through this analysis, it is revealed that groundwater level, soil moisture, and soil temperature are the most valuable predictors for drought conditions. Principal component analysis indicated this as well, with similarity between soil metrics in the first principal component, and groundwater level serving in the second principal component. Several supervised learning methods were applied, with random forest methods performing best in the binary classification task with 98% accuracy.

While random forest performed best of the methods tests, decision trees and SVM could potentially be improved via hyperparameter tuning. Neural networks could similarly benefit from further sensitivity analysis, and more detailed analysis of sensitivity analysis could clarify trends in changing the number of layers or neurons.

This analysis focused on binary classification of drought conditions. However, as emphasized by the levels of drought severity provided by Drought Monitor resources, drought is a spectrum. Future analysis could consider the calculated Drought Severity and Coverage Index (DSCI), which describes drought severity as a single continuous variable. Modeling a continuous variable allows for regression methodologies, which could translate to time series prediction as well.

While it is easy to fall into the data science trap of looking at problems as purely theoretical, it is crucial to consider how accurate drought prediction models can help address future drought concerns or feed into wildfire specific models. It is certainly useful to understand how various models perform in Los Angeles to establish a methodology for other regions or data problems.
